{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507932"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.28,0.07,0.45,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31607"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1102"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34270"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman, G3P2, at 32 weeks gestation presents to her General Practice clinic with a 10-day history of headache. This headache is constant and has been gradually worsening. She describes it as diffuse scalp tenderness that is not relieved by rest or lying down. She has no symptoms of aura and no history of migraines. Her medical history includes anxiety and unprovoked deep vein thrombosis. Her current pregnancy has been uncomplicated and she has no prior history of pre-eclampsia. There were no complications in her two previous pregnancies, and both resulted in term vaginal births. Her family history is unremarkable. She is currently undergoing a stressful situation at work and feels like that is the likely cause of the headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 125/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is slight blurring of the margins of the optic discs bilaterally on fundoscopy. Her full blood count, liver function tests, and urinalysis are normal. Despite suitable analgesia the headache persists.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiotocography","Blood pressure monitoring","Foetal ultrasound","Brain MRI","Referral to perinatal mental health services"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with risk factors for cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (CVST) including being female, pregnant and having past deep vein thrombosis, as well as red flag symptoms (constant gradually worsening headache and evidence of raised intracranial pressure). \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E would be the investigation of choice for a patient with risk factors for CVST, with the diagnostic finding being absent or reduced blood flow in one of the venous sinuses. An MRI is the investigation of choice due to the undifferentiated presentation of the patient and the presence of raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the patient\u0027s blood pressure of 125/72 mmHg and investigations are normal, it is less likely that pre-eclampsia is the diagnosis. Pre-eclampsia investigations would include \u003Cstrong\u003Efoetal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood pressure monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E. These investigations would be initiated by high blood pressure readings or significant proteinuria and therefore both options are not suitable in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiotocography\u003C/strong\u003E is suitable after diagnosing pre-eclampsia and gestational hypertension, but as pre-eclampsia is not diagnosed here, it would be less suitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf her headaches were due to stress, psychological support (\u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to perinatal mental health services\u003C/strong\u003E) would be warranted, but other diagnoses not to miss need to be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Consider and investigate patients for cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (CVST) in pregnancy, especially those with risk factors such as previous venous thromboembolism."],"references":["Iles, S, Normal pregnancy and antenatal care. In: Symonds I, Arulkumaran S, editors. Essential Obstetrics and Gynaecology, 5th edn. Elsevier; 2013; Chapter 7:95.","Hypertension in pregnancy: diagnosis and management, NICE guideline [NG133]. In: National Institute for Healthcare and Excellence [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng133/chapter/Recommendations#management-of-pre-eclampsia","Ropper, AH, Klein JP, Cerebral Venous Thrombosis. N Engl J Med. 2021;385:59-64. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra2106545"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31607"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31607"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-12T12:18:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-22T22:16:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2692"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46777"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1091"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Headache","synonyms":["Headaches"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-29T10:31:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T13:47:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api